WHEREAS, Susan Long went on to serve as the marketing and management
coordinator for Mountain Brook Village and later the administrator at Atria Weston Place before
joining Baptist Health System in 1996 as the director of Senior Services; and
WHEREAS, during her nine-year tenure with Baptist Health System, Ms. Long
developed and marketed eight Senior Health Centers targeting patients aged fifty and older; her
innovative approach led to the creation of comprehensive ancillary services, including social
work, dietitian consultations, exercise programs, support groups, immunization clinics, foot care,
massage therapy, and wellness initiatives; and
WHEREAS, she later lent her expertise to Covenant Health and East Tennessee
Personal Care Service, where she continued advocating for underserved older populations; her
skill in communication and outreach helped amplify the needs and voices of vulnerable
individuals in the community; and
WHEREAS, in 2013, Susan Long was named the third director of the Knoxville-Knox
County Community Action Committee (CAC) Office on Aging, in which capacity she led a team
of fifty employees and oversaw twenty-four programs, steering the agency with compassion and
vision and effecting meaningful change for residents of the region; and
WHEREAS, even after her retirement from the Office on Aging, she remained active in
contributing to special projects at CAC; her leadership during the COVID-19 pandemic included
coordinating vaccine clinics and wellness outreach, and she played pivotal roles in the 2020
Census efforts and CAC's sixtieth anniversary celebration; and
WHEREAS, in addition to her professional endeavors, Susan Long has served her
community as a ruling elder at Sequoyah Hills Presbyterian Church, vice president of Keep
Knoxville Beautiful, a member of the CAC Board of Directors, president of the John T. O'Connor
Senior Center Advisory Board, vice president of Second Harvest Food Bank, a member of the
